Doc Del:<br><br>
We who care have witnessed a tragedy here!  A very special person such as yourself has been fouled when he came forth with honest revelation.  <br>
What I derived from your story was the extraordinary effort that a young man (you) put forth to do something that you felt was special.  It is also very apparent that you honor the military service of men in your family.<br>
I don't see weakness from you dropping out...instead I see exlempary courage from your attempts on bad legs.<br>
There is something special about medics and corpmen..they are driven to serve their brothers.  When the company stops to take a well deserved rest...the medic is busy tending blisters, heat exhaustion etc....medics don't get breaks.  Medics carry a lot more than the average grunt...for some reason the dumb shits try to carry a MASH hospital on their backs.  They carry extra water for those who become ill or dehydrated.  Often when a grunt is evacuated a medic will carry team gear such as a mortar base plate or extra ammo that the casuality no longer can carry.<br>
Perhaps your exposure to those wounded vets in Tripler sentenced you to a &quot;rough row to hoe&quot; ... simply because you care about humans!<br>
When I was paralyzed at Camp Zama, a lot of my ward buddies had missing legs and feet but they were not short on spirit. I was told that I would never walk again but their spirit (not just mine) gave me the strength and will to walk again. In two years of combat helicopter flying I hauled a lot of wounded men and got an appreciation for what medics do for their brothers in battle!  Four gunshot wounds and a broken back gave me a personal appreciation and love for medics.  But, I would have loved you and your type anyway for all your sacrifice.  I was a medic with the 82ABD before flight school.  In Vietnam, when I flew out with a dead medic in the back, I would pull down my tinted visor to hide my tears.<br>
Cookie has the highest regard for you..I'm sure that he didn't believe that it was you...I'm glad that I held my fire.  Spatz is enjoying some sick pleasure in seeing the seeds of his mistrust hurt a combat vet.<br>
Thanks for your powerful story, Doc Del...You stand pretty damn tall in my eyes...legs or no legs.  Welcome Home!<br><br>
Your Friend and Brother - Ed<br>

